+| `F_SS(mu)` | pro-circuit | engineered-sign sparse-triad family with frozen sign sheet `sigma_SS`; desired channels are sign-coherent and normalized to unit on-template mass, while each spectator class is `O(mu)` with `0 < mu <= 1/12` | `engineered helical sign patterns`, `sparse triad geometries` |
+| `F_SL(rho)` | pro-circuit | scale-separated family with frozen sign sheet `sigma_SL`; desired channels carry unit on-template mass on `I`, trigger starts small but nonzero, and spectator leakage is nonzero but `O(rho)` on the normalized window with `0 < rho <= 1/12` | `scale-separated packets`, `leakage exists but may be dynamically negligible` |
+
+### Why These Four Families Are The Right Step-4 Menu
+
+- `[VERIFIED]` The anti-circuit side must include Beltrami fragility,
+  mirror completion, near-degenerate geometry, and tiny-trigger stress because
+  those are the adverse cases the winning chain names explicitly.
+- `[VERIFIED]` The pro-circuit side must include engineered sign patterns,
